ML and Analytics of Molecular Dynamics Simulations of BChE

Introduction

Proteins and ligands (such as small-molecule drugs) exist in conformational equilibrium. Knowledge of the total set of conformations (binding modes) provides a more complete picture of the protein-ligand binding behaviour which can be used for rational drug design. We apply a novel method to study butyrylcholinesterase inhibited by dialkyl aryl phosphates.

We can study the space of conformation using simulations. We can produce a large number of snapshots of the protein-ligand system at different points in time. Because of ergodicity the ensemble of snapshots over time average out to the ensemble of many proteins and ligands at the same point in time, as one would find in-vivo or in-vitro.

Therefore, we: 1. Perform simulations 2. Partition simulation snapshots into binding modes 3. Report the binding modes

Technologies

This project made extensive use of the Python3 libraries: - pandas - sklearn - matplotlib

Method Overview

Performing simulations

To perform simulations, we used the Folding@home distributed computing network to compute simulations prepared using the molecular dynamics suite GROMACS. In total, we prepared over 1 million snapshots from over 100 µs of simulations.

Ascertaining Binding modes

The creation of binding modes can be roughly broken down into 2 parts 1. Transforming the snapshots into vectors onto which the techniques of clustering can be applied

For Step 1, we used a novel descriptor vector (fingerprint). The list of components in this vector is each amino acid in the protein joined with each functional group within the ligand the list of amino acids within the protein. The component is the number of atoms in each amino acid that is within 5 Angstroms of any atom in that functional group. By studying what ligand atoms are close to what amino acid atoms, we capture the intermolecular forces that govern a binding mode

  1. Applying clustring algorithms onto those vectors

For step 2, we applied K-means on the descriptor vectors. K-means is a good choice here because of the large number of datapoints to be clustered and large descriptor vectors. K-means is a challenging choice because the number of clusters, k, which represent different protein-ligand conformations, must be specified. To determine this, we used a novel approach where we looked at the variance and rage over repeated clusterings. We chose this approach because inertial graphs showed no elbow and we reserve the silhuoette approach for cluster confirmation because we lack a ground truth. To explain this, we show the following figure.

In this image, it is clear that k is 4 or 3.

For a given k, if one were to invoke K means multiple times, then one could sort the populations of the resulting clusters. When K is a number for which there is a “natural” clustering, here 3 or 4, then the populations of all of the clusters will have very littel variance. If, on the otherhand, one uses an incorrect number of clusters, such as 5 in (c) or (d), then K means will be forced to assign cluster membership in an intrinsically non-reproducible way.

This, in turn, leads to variance in the population of the clusters. Therefore, we can use this tehcnique to ascertain one or more valid K values for a dataset. While smaller numbers without variance are valid choices, larger numbers allow for finer cluster-structure to be revealed. As an example from one of the alkyl aryl phosphates, we produced

Where the y axis indicates the value of k and the red and blue coloring represent the variance and range over 10 repeated clusterings. Visually, there are 7 bindings modes for this system.

Results

For reporting results, we first perform 2 sanity checks and then share the contacts that are revealed

Ensemble Equilibration

To confirm that our simulations and partitions are valid (as well as choose a subset of snapshots), we plot the populations over time. Stable simulations show asymptotic behavior over time, which we observe.

[ ]:

Silhuoette Matrix

Because we lack readily obtainable ground truth, we use the silhuoette coefficient to evaluate the cluster quality. Here we show the result for the same ligand whose k-selection graphic is shown above.

For each cluster, a random subset of descriptor vectors are chosen and associated with each cluster number (ordered by population). An RMSD similarity operation is performed between each vector, with more similar vectors resulting in a green color. Hence, we see that the clusters that we obtain are more similar than they are dissimilar. Interestingly, the smaller-k option (4) reveals itself as a macro-structure block of general similarity.

Contact Tables

Confident in our simulations and clustering, we report results in a compact, biologist-friendly result, shown here.

The rows are binding modes and the columns are amino acids that are found in the binding pocket of butyrylcholinesterase. The most prominent functional group and correspondingly dominant binding type is show as each entry. Again, we see large similarity between the first 4 binding modes, but very different behaviour for the less populated modes.
